What to make of Winona Ryder and Pen√©lope Cruz defending Johnny Depp?

Two women say Depp never hurt them, ergo, he could never hurt any woman? Ah, were life only that simple. It recently emerged that Cruz ‚Äì who has worked with Depp three times ‚Äì filed a declaration stating that Depp is ‚Äúalways kind to everyone around‚Äù. Meanwhile, Ryder ‚Äì who went out with him three decades ago ‚Äì said in an interview: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to call anyone a liar, but from my experience of Johnny, it is impossible to believe such horrific allegations are true.‚Äù I think you just called someone a liar, Winona.

Ryder and Cruz both know Depp personally, and it is entirely fair for them to share their personal experiences of being involved with him. But that is what those experiences are ‚Äì personal ‚Äì and is it really ‚Äúimpossible‚Äù for Ryder to believe that Depp abused his ex-wife Amber Heard, as Heard has claimed and Depp strongly denies? I would suggest that Ryder needs to expand her imagination a little here. I am delighted for her that she had such a happy relationship with Depp. But after they broke up he went out with Kate Moss and, one night in 1994, guests in New York‚Äôs Mark Hotel heard what was described as ‚Äúshattering glass, snapping wood and loud domestic squabbling‚Äù . When the police turned up, Moss was sitting in a trashed room and Depp was ‚Äúin a state of possible intoxication‚Äù. He was arrested for criminal mischief, a charge a judge later dismissed, and Depp paid more than $11,000 in damages to the hotel.

Now, trashing a hotel room is not the same as beating one‚Äôs wife, and 1994 was a long time ago ‚Äì more‚Äôs the pity in scary 2020. But is it really ‚Äúimpossible to believe‚Äù that a man who once got so drunk he violently ripped apart a room with his girlfriend in it could, 25 years later, possibly get drunk and violent with his wife?

Depp is suing Heard for defamation, and has always vehemently denied abusing her, so it is entirely reasonable that his friends would speak up in his defence as character witnesses. But when I hear women say: ‚ÄúHe didn‚Äôt beat me, ergo it‚Äôs mad to think he could have beaten his ex-wife!‚Äù, it reminds me of people such as Len McCluskey and Ken Loach, who airily insist they haven‚Äôt seen any antisemitism in the Labour party, therefore it isn‚Äôt a problem. There is something fascinatingly narcissistic in believing that one‚Äôs own individual experience reveals all: McCluskey and Loach are not Jewish; Cruz and Ryder were not recently married to Depp. So their thoughts on these respective matters are, to be blunt, of limited relevance.
